[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":639},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started\u002F":614,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2022\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started\u002F":623},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20220313\u002F1135671172\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":595,"date":596,"description":597,"extension":598,"lang":599,"meta":600,"navigation":501,"path":601,"readingMinutes":602,"seo":603,"standalone":604,"stem":605,"tags":606,"tldr":611,"updated":596,"url":612,"__hash__":613},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fnodejs-mango-22-mocha-getting-started.md","(22) The Frontend Dev Force-Fed Mango - Getting Started with Mocha","1003230955",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":588},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,36,65,75,85,159,165,167,172,216,223,226,243,275,282,286,297,347,362,368,374,454,461,567,570,577,584],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"In the earlier chapters we got a quick look at Mocha and installed it, but we never actually started writing any real syntax. So this time I'll walk through some of the common syntax you'll bump into all the time.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"getting-started-with-mocha","Getting started with Mocha",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35],{},"First, let's create a ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"test"," folder inside our Express project, and add a ",[28,33,34],{},"test_helper.js"," file. You don't need much in there yet, because we want to get familiar with the basics of Mocha first — and these are the bits of syntax we'll be leaning on later. Here's the list:",[37,38,39,45,50,55,60],"ul",{},[40,41,42],"li",{},[28,43,44],{},"before",[40,46,47],{},[28,48,49],{},"beforeEach",[40,51,52],{},[28,53,54],{},"describe",[40,56,57],{},[28,58,59],{},"it",[40,61,62],{},[28,63,64],{},"xit",[17,66,67,68,71,72,74],{},"Plus ",[28,69,70],{},"assert",". One thing to note here: ",[28,73,70],{}," is the assertion library that Node.js ships with, not Mocha's. The reason is that Mocha doesn't come with its own assertion library, so we just use the one built into Node.js.",[17,76,77,78,81,82,84],{},"Before we start, open up your ",[28,79,80],{},"package.json"," and add a ",[28,83,30],{}," command like this:",[86,87,92],"pre",{"className":88,"code":89,"language":90,"meta":91,"style":91},"language-json shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","{\n  ...\n  \"scripts\": {\n    ...\n    \"test\": \"mocha\",\n  },\n  ...\n}\n","json","",[28,93,94,103,110,120,126,142,148,153],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,96,99],"span",{"class":97,"line":98},"line",1,[95,100,102],{"class":101},"sMAXC","{\n",[95,104,106],{"class":97,"line":105},2,[95,107,109],{"class":108},"szH_Z","  ...\n",[95,111,113,117],{"class":97,"line":112},3,[95,114,116],{"class":115},"sKpQp","  \"scripts\"",[95,118,119],{"class":101},": {\n",[95,121,123],{"class":97,"line":122},4,[95,124,125],{"class":108},"    ...\n",[95,127,129,132,135,139],{"class":97,"line":128},5,[95,130,131],{"class":115},"    \"test\"",[95,133,134],{"class":101},": ",[95,136,138],{"class":137},"sTRMh","\"mocha\"",[95,140,141],{"class":101},",\n",[95,143,145],{"class":97,"line":144},6,[95,146,147],{"class":101},"  },\n",[95,149,151],{"class":97,"line":150},7,[95,152,109],{"class":108},[95,154,156],{"class":97,"line":155},8,[95,157,158],{"class":101},"}\n",[17,160,161,162,164],{},"Once that's added, head back to ",[28,163,34],{}," and we're ready to go.",[12,166,44],{"id":44},[17,168,169,171],{},[28,170,44],{}," means \"run this stuff before the tests run.\" So the basic syntax looks like this:",[86,173,177],{"className":174,"code":175,"language":176,"meta":91,"style":91},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","before(() => {\n  console.log('before');\n})\n","js",[28,178,179,194,211],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,180,181,184,187,191],{"class":97,"line":98},[95,182,44],{"class":183},"sj_SG",[95,185,186],{"class":101},"(() ",[95,188,190],{"class":189},"sWyjQ","=>",[95,192,193],{"class":101}," {\n",[95,195,196,199,202,205,208],{"class":97,"line":105},[95,197,198],{"class":101},"  console.",[95,200,201],{"class":183},"log",[95,203,204],{"class":101},"(",[95,206,207],{"class":137},"'before'",[95,209,210],{"class":101},");\n",[95,212,213],{"class":97,"line":112},[95,214,215],{"class":101},"})\n",[17,217,218,219,222],{},"The flip side is ",[28,220,221],{},"after",", which runs its contents only after all the tests have finished.",[12,224,49],{"id":225},"beforeeach",[17,227,228,230,231,233,234,236,237,239,240,242],{},[28,229,49],{}," means \"before each test runs,\" it runs its contents once each time. Note that this is different from ",[28,232,44],{}," — ",[28,235,44],{}," only runs once, whereas ",[28,238,49],{}," runs once before every single test. You write it the same way as ",[28,241,44],{},":",[86,244,246],{"className":174,"code":245,"language":176,"meta":91,"style":91},"beforeEach(() => {\n  console.log('beforeEach');\n})\n",[28,247,248,258,271],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,249,250,252,254,256],{"class":97,"line":98},[95,251,49],{"class":183},[95,253,186],{"class":101},[95,255,190],{"class":189},[95,257,193],{"class":101},[95,259,260,262,264,266,269],{"class":97,"line":105},[95,261,198],{"class":101},[95,263,201],{"class":183},[95,265,204],{"class":101},[95,267,268],{"class":137},"'beforeEach'",[95,270,210],{"class":101},[95,272,273],{"class":97,"line":112},[95,274,215],{"class":101},[17,276,277,278,281],{},"And the counterpart is ",[28,279,280],{},"afterEach",", which runs its contents after each test finishes.",[12,283,285],{"id":284},"describe-and-it","describe and it",[17,287,288,290,291,293,294,296],{},[28,289,54],{}," describes what a test block is doing. Think of it as a grouping concept — you usually have a bunch of tests inside it, so it tends to pair up with ",[28,292,59],{},". And ",[28,295,59],{}," is the thing you actually plan to test. You write it like this:",[86,298,300],{"className":174,"code":299,"language":176,"meta":91,"style":91},"describe('First test', () => {\n  it('Testing whether 1 + 1 equals 2', () => {\n    ...\n  })\n})\n",[28,301,302,318,334,338,343],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,303,304,306,308,311,314,316],{"class":97,"line":98},[95,305,54],{"class":183},[95,307,204],{"class":101},[95,309,310],{"class":137},"'First test'",[95,312,313],{"class":101},", () ",[95,315,190],{"class":189},[95,317,193],{"class":101},[95,319,320,323,325,328,330,332],{"class":97,"line":105},[95,321,322],{"class":183},"  it",[95,324,204],{"class":101},[95,326,327],{"class":137},"'Testing whether 1 + 1 equals 2'",[95,329,313],{"class":101},[95,331,190],{"class":189},[95,333,193],{"class":101},[95,335,336],{"class":97,"line":112},[95,337,125],{"class":189},[95,339,340],{"class":97,"line":122},[95,341,342],{"class":101},"  })\n",[95,344,345],{"class":97,"line":128},[95,346,215],{"class":101},[17,348,349,350,352,353,355,356,358,359,361],{},"That's the basic usage of ",[28,351,54],{}," and ",[28,354,59],{},". Now ",[28,357,64],{}," is a pretty special one. Basically, if you've got a test you've already written but don't want to run for now, you can use ",[28,360,64],{}," to skip it. You might be thinking — why not just delete it?",[17,363,364,365,367],{},"The main reason is that sometimes you only want to temporarily skip a test, not actually delete it, because it might contain earlier logic you'll want again. If you delete it, it becomes a real pain to go back and dig it up later. So my suggestion is to use ",[28,366,64],{}," to skip it while keeping the original test logic around.",[17,369,370,371,373],{},"Okay, so here's a question — how do we verify the result? This is where the ",[28,372,70],{}," I mentioned earlier comes in. It asserts whether the result is actually true. For example:",[86,375,377],{"className":174,"code":376,"language":176,"meta":91,"style":91},"describe('First test', () => {\n  it('Testing whether 1 + 1 equals 2', () => {\n    const a = 1 + 1;\n    assert(a === 2);\n  })\n})\n",[28,378,379,393,407,430,446,450],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,380,381,383,385,387,389,391],{"class":97,"line":98},[95,382,54],{"class":183},[95,384,204],{"class":101},[95,386,310],{"class":137},[95,388,313],{"class":101},[95,390,190],{"class":189},[95,392,193],{"class":101},[95,394,395,397,399,401,403,405],{"class":97,"line":105},[95,396,322],{"class":183},[95,398,204],{"class":101},[95,400,327],{"class":137},[95,402,313],{"class":101},[95,404,190],{"class":189},[95,406,193],{"class":101},[95,408,409,412,416,419,422,425,427],{"class":97,"line":112},[95,410,411],{"class":189},"    const",[95,413,415],{"class":414},"sCcAr"," a",[95,417,418],{"class":189}," =",[95,420,421],{"class":414}," 1",[95,423,424],{"class":189}," +",[95,426,421],{"class":414},[95,428,429],{"class":101},";\n",[95,431,432,435,438,441,444],{"class":97,"line":122},[95,433,434],{"class":183},"    assert",[95,436,437],{"class":101},"(a ",[95,439,440],{"class":189},"===",[95,442,443],{"class":414}," 2",[95,445,210],{"class":101},[95,447,448],{"class":97,"line":128},[95,449,342],{"class":101},[95,451,452],{"class":97,"line":144},[95,453,215],{"class":101},[17,455,456,457,460],{},"Once you've written that, you can run ",[28,458,459],{},"npm run test"," to see the result. Here's a complete example so you can make sure yours runs correctly:",[86,462,464],{"className":174,"code":463,"language":176,"meta":91,"style":91},"const { describe, it } = require('mocha');\n\ndescribe('First test', () => {\n  it('Testing whether 1 + 1 equals 2', () => {\n    const a = 1 + 1;\n    assert(a === 2);\n  })\n})\n",[28,465,466,497,503,517,531,547,559,563],{"__ignoreMap":91},[95,467,468,471,474,476,479,481,484,487,490,492,495],{"class":97,"line":98},[95,469,470],{"class":189},"const",[95,472,473],{"class":101}," { ",[95,475,54],{"class":414},[95,477,478],{"class":101},", ",[95,480,59],{"class":414},[95,482,483],{"class":101}," } ",[95,485,486],{"class":189},"=",[95,488,489],{"class":183}," require",[95,491,204],{"class":101},[95,493,494],{"class":137},"'mocha'",[95,496,210],{"class":101},[95,498,499],{"class":97,"line":105},[95,500,502],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":501},true,"\n",[95,504,505,507,509,511,513,515],{"class":97,"line":112},[95,506,54],{"class":183},[95,508,204],{"class":101},[95,510,310],{"class":137},[95,512,313],{"class":101},[95,514,190],{"class":189},[95,516,193],{"class":101},[95,518,519,521,523,525,527,529],{"class":97,"line":122},[95,520,322],{"class":183},[95,522,204],{"class":101},[95,524,327],{"class":137},[95,526,313],{"class":101},[95,528,190],{"class":189},[95,530,193],{"class":101},[95,532,533,535,537,539,541,543,545],{"class":97,"line":128},[95,534,411],{"class":189},[95,536,415],{"class":414},[95,538,418],{"class":189},[95,540,421],{"class":414},[95,542,424],{"class":189},[95,544,421],{"class":414},[95,546,429],{"class":101},[95,548,549,551,553,555,557],{"class":97,"line":144},[95,550,434],{"class":183},[95,552,437],{"class":101},[95,554,440],{"class":189},[95,556,443],{"class":414},[95,558,210],{"class":101},[95,560,561],{"class":97,"line":150},[95,562,342],{"class":101},[95,564,565],{"class":97,"line":155},[95,566,215],{"class":101},[17,568,569],{},"Once it runs, you should see a green checkmark, which means your test passed.",[17,571,572],{},[573,574],"img",{"alt":575,"src":576},"Test passed","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FNodejs\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202022-02-26%2022.20.32.png",[17,578,579,580,583],{},"Honestly, once you've got these techniques down, you've got at least 60–70% of the testing basics covered. For the rest of the chapters, we'll be writing ",[28,581,582],{},"Mongoose"," from a testing angle.",[585,586,587],"styl